(42, 23, 41, 40, 27, 24, 24, 'this man hath done nothing amiss', 'Innocence of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the innocence of Jesus. In Luke, the criminal acknowledges Jesus'' lack of wrongdoing, while in Matthew, Pilate declares Jesus a ''just person,'' reinforcing the theme of His innocence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 41, 60, 1, 19, 19, 'hath done nothing amiss', 'Connection of Innocence and Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of innocence, as the criminal acknowledges that Jesus ''hath done nothing amiss,'' paralleling the description of Christ as ''a lamb without blemish and without spot.'' Both passages emphasize the purity and righteousness of Jesus in the context of sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
